    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 4, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🔓 Google Opens Up Gemma 4 Completely — Apache 2.0, No Strings Attached\n\nGoogle released Gemma 4, a family of four open-weight models built from the same research as Gemini 3 — and for the first time in the series, every model ships under Apache 2.0, with zero commercial restrictions.\n\n- **The lineup:** E2B, E4B, 26B MoE, and 31B Dense. All support 256K context windows, native vision and audio, and over 140 languages. A \"we checked every box\" release.\n- **The Apache 2.0 move:** previous Gemma versions blocked commercial use. Google just quietly removed all restrictions. The open-source community's reaction was predictably enthusiastic. Competitors took notes.\n\n*Open-weight, Apache 2.0, multimodal, 256K context. Google is trying very hard to win something here.*\n\n**Sources:** [Google Open Source Blog](https://opensource.googleblog.com/2026/03/gemma-4-expanding-the-gemmaverse-with-apache-20.html) | [9to5Google](https://9to5google.com/2026/04/02/google-gemma-4/)\n\n---\n\n## 🔐 Anthropic Built a Model So Dangerous It's Briefing Congress Instead of Launching It\n\nAnthropic accidentally revealed a model called Claude Mythos (internally \"Capybara\") when a draft blog post leaked from a publicly accessible cache. The model is a \"step change\" beyond Opus — and Anthropic is quietly briefing US officials about its cybersecurity implications rather than shipping it.\n\n- **The capabilities:** Mythos scores dramatically higher on cybersecurity benchmarks, capable of rapidly finding and exploiting software vulnerabilities at non-human speed. Anthropic describes large-scale cyberattacks as \"much more likely in 2026 and beyond\" because of it.\n- **The strategy:** an AI company deliberately not releasing its most powerful model. The race-to-ship instinct has apparently met a wall called \"we built something alarming.\"\n\n*An AI company voluntarily sitting on its most capable model and briefing governments instead. The bar for news just changed.*\n\n**Sources:** [Fortune](https://fortune.com/2026/03/26/anthropic-says-testing-mythos-powerful-new-ai-model-after-data-leak-reveals-its-existence-step-change-in-capabilities/) | [CNN Business](https://www.cnn.com/2026/04/03/tech/anthropic-mythos-ai-cybersecurity)\n\n---\n\n## 📺 OpenAI Just Bought Its Own Fan Media (Editorial Independence Sold Separately)\n\nOpenAI acquired TBPN — a daily founder-led tech talk show with $30M+ in annual revenue — in a deal reportedly worth hundreds of millions. TBPN will retain \"editorial independence\" but report to Chris Lehane, OpenAI's chief political operative.\n\n- **What TBPN is:** a YouTube and X show deeply embedded in SF tech culture, extremely favorable to AI founders. OpenAI just bought its natural press corps.\n- **The Lehane detail:** Chris Lehane is not a tech executive. He's a political operative. The show that covers OpenAI now reports to OpenAI's political operative. (Fine. Probably fine.)\n\n*\"Editorial independence\" — maintained under the direct supervision of a political operative. (Checks out.)*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/04/02/openai-acquires-tbpn-the-buzzy-founder-led-business-talk-show/) | [CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/04/02/openai-acquires-tech-podcast-tbpn.html) | [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/04/02/openai-acquires-tbpn)\n\n---\n\n## 🤖 Amazon and Qualcomm Just Bet €1 Billion on a German Humanoid Startup\n\nNeura Robotics closed a €1 billion ($1.2B) round led by Amazon and Qualcomm, valuing it at ~€4 billion. The company is launching a Porsche-designed Gen 3 humanoid and integrating NVIDIA's Cosmos world models into its development pipeline.\n\n- **The raise context:** €1B for a European humanoid startup is the kind of thing that would have been a punchline in 2022. It is now a Tuesday announcement.\n- **The Porsche detail:** the Gen 3 humanoid was designed by Porsche. A sportscar manufacturer is now designing robots. The logic tracks — both optimize for performance under stress with a premium packaging constraint.\n\n*Porsche-designed, Amazon-backed, Qualcomm-powered. Your humanoid robot has a better resume than most engineers.*\n\n**Sources:** [Bloomberg](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-04-01/europe-vies-to-be-humanoid-robot-leader-in-global-tech-race)\n\n---\n\n## 🎬 Gig Workers Are Performing Household Chores on Camera to Train Robots ($100M+ Market)\n\nMIT Technology Review named it a 2026 Breakthrough Technology: gig workers recording themselves doing dishes, folding laundry, and performing industrial tasks at home — then selling that footage to robotics companies as physical AI training data. The market already exceeds $100 million per year.\n\n- **How it works:** brokers like Micro1 connect robotics firms with workers who have a camera and a kitchen. Humanoid robots need massive real-world motion data to learn physical tasks. Gig workers are now the supply chain for robot behavior.\n- **The uncomfortable math:** \"gig workers train robots\" and \"robots will replace gig workers\" can be simultaneously true. MIT Technology Review is apparently comfortable with this.\n\n*You can now be displaced by the footage you sold of yourself doing the dishes.*\n\n**Sources:** [MIT Technology Review](https://www.technologyreview.com/2026/04/01/1134863/humanoid-data-training-gig-economy-2026-breakthrough-technology/)"
